    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1952-05-31T10:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1952-05-31T10:00:00-05:00" n="157"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d157">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">795B.00/6–152: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Charge in Korea (<persName corresp="#p_LEA1" type="from"
                            >Lightner</persName>) to the <gloss type="to">Department of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d157fn1">This telegram, upon receipt at the Department of
                        State, was relayed to the Department of Defense.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret<lb/>
                            <gloss target="#t_niact1">niact</gloss>
                        </hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Pusan</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1952-06-01T00:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 1, 1952—midnight</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1229. Rptd info <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss>, <gloss
                        target="#t_EUSAK1">EUSAK</gloss> Advance <gloss target="#t_DIP1">DIP</gloss>
                    245 by other means. Re <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 1228, June
                        1,<note n="2" xml:id="d157fn2">
                        <hi rend="italic">
                            <ref target="#d157">Supra</ref>
                        </hi>.</note> rptd <gloss target="#t_CINCUNC1">CINCUNC</gloss> and <gloss
                        target="#t_EUSAK1">EUSAK</gloss> Advance as <gloss target="#t_DIP1"
                        >DIP</gloss> 244.</p>
                <p>There may be other alternatives to <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> martial
                    law which might be tried pending decision and clearance to embark that
                    irrevocable action. I refer to measures touched on in previous messages, steps
                    beyond normal diplomatic approaches but short of <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                        >UNC</gloss> intervention.</p>
                <list>
                    <label>1.</label>
                    <item>Announcement withhold economic aid (except relief) along lines mentioned
                            <gloss target="#t_Embtel1">Embtel</gloss> 1216, May 31.<note n="3"
                            xml:id="d157fn3">Not printed (795.00/5–3152).</note>
                    </item>
                    <pb facs="0315" n="281" xml:id="pg_281"/>
                    <label>2.</label>
                    <item>Movement of Naval vessels to Pusan harbor.</item>
                    <label>3.</label>
                    <item>Movement <gloss target="#t_UNC1">UNC</gloss> troop units to areas near
                        Pusan.</item>
                    <label>4.</label>
                    <item>Demands.</item>
                    <label>5.</label>
                    <item>Exploration possibility arranging have <gloss target="#t_ROK1">ROK</gloss>
                        Army and Naval units act in much same way as <gloss target="#t_UNC1"
                            >UNC</gloss> martial law envisaged.</item>
                </list>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_LEA1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Lightner</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
